3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etrunks\u003C/strong\u003E of the brachial plexus are located in the posterior triangle of the neck. The roots of the brachial plexus emerge from the intervertebral foramina and pass between the anterior and middle scalene muscles, they then go on to form the trunks in the posterior triangle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDivisions\u003C/strong\u003E - Are located behind the clavicle\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranches\u003C/strong\u003E - Arise from the cords and are located in the axilla\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECords\u003C/strong\u003E - Are located in the axilla\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERoots\u003C/strong\u003E - Are located between the anterior and middle scalene muscles, before forming the trunks\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe brachial plexus is responsible for the motor and sensory innervation of the upper limb.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The roots and trunks of the brachial plexus are located in the posterior triangle of the neck.","The brachial plexus is a network of nerves that supplies the upper limb, originating from the spinal nerves C5 to T1."],"references":["Polcaro L, Charlick M, Daly DT. Anatomy, Head and Neck: Brachial Plexus. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK531473/","Sakellariou VI, Badilas NK, Mazis GA, Stavropoulos NA, Kotoulas HK, Kyriakopoulos S, Tagkalegkas I, Sofianos IP. Brachial plexus injuries in adults: evaluation and diagnostic approach. ISRN Orthop. 2014 Feb 9;2014:726103. doi: 10.1155/2014/726103. PMID: 24967130; PMC